A debounce function ensures that a function is not called too frequently, especially useful for events like scrolling or resizing.

```javascript
// Define the debounce function
function debounce(func, wait) {
    let timeout;
    return function(...args) {
        const context = this;
        if (timeout) clearTimeout(timeout);
        timeout = setTimeout(() => {
            func.apply(context, args);
        }, wait);
    };
}

// Example usage:
window.addEventListener('resize', debounce(() => {
    console.log('Window resized');
}, 250));
```

In the example above, the console log will only trigger once the user stops resizing the window for at least 250 milliseconds.
